{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17532664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17532664"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:29:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:29:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14698"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14698"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0,0.94,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7391"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58087"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7391"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43546"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2975"},{"type":"tags","id":"3589"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5884"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18030"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39276"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58087"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of irregular menstrual periods and occasional milky discharge from both breasts. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is not pregnant and is not breastfeeding. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Visual fields are normal to confrontation. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following hormones is most likely to be abnormal?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Follicle stimulating hormone","Growth hormone","Prolactin","Thyroid stimulating hormone","Adrenocorticotropic hormone"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of a prolactinoma including galactorrhoea (milky nipple discharge) and menstrual irregularity. These symptoms strongly suggest hyperprolactinaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlactin\u003C/strong\u003E elevation is the defining biochemical abnormality in prolactinoma. Prolactin has direct effects on breast tissue, stimulating milk production, and can suppress gonadotropin-releasing hormone, leading to menstrual irregularities and infertility. Especially in post-menopausal females, patients can experience symptoms related to mass effect such as headache and changes in vision. In males with prolactinoma, symptoms can include reduced libido, and erectile or ejaculatory dysfunction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicle stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E may be suppressed secondary to hyperprolactinaemia but is not the primary hormonal abnormality. \u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth hormone\u003C/strong\u003E excess (acromegaly) typically presents with changes in facial features, enlargement of hands and feet, and metabolic disturbances. While both conditions can arise from pituitary tumours, the presentation here is not consistent with growth hormone excess. \u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E abnormalities present with symptoms of hyper- or hypothyroidism such as weight changes, heat or cold intolerance, and changes in energy levels. While hypothyroidism can cause mild prolactin elevation, it would not typically cause such marked galactorrhoea. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenocorticotropic hormone\u003C/strong\u003E excess (Cushing\u0027s disease) presents with central obesity, muscle weakness, easy bruising, and striae. These features are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of galactorrhoea and menstrual irregularity is highly specific for hyperprolactinaemia. Other causes of hyperprolactinaemia should be considered including medications (especially antipsychotics), pregnancy, and hypothyroidism, but in this case, a prolactinoma is most likely given the clinical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pre-menopausal females with a prolactinoma will often present with menstrual irregularities or amenorrhoea."],"references":["Rajini Kanth R. Yatavelli, Kamal Bhusal. Prolactinoma. In: StatPearls [online]. 2018. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459347/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43546"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14698"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43546"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-28T21:09:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-28T21:10:32+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7391"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58087"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.c